nting gateway to the social circle of the resort. As the date of Kenzie's seventieth birthday party approaches, Dalton journeys to the island at the request of Miss Sickert, who requires his assistance in the composition of a will. Also travelling to the island are Dalton's stepson, Nandy, whose relationship with his stepfather threatens to become distant beyond repair, and Bree, who has come to celebrate her father's birthday. By coincidence, a miraculous reunion is brought about when Bree realises that the man sat next to her on the flight to West Palm Beach is her uncle Dalton, and the two travellers are met at the airport by Nandy and Kenzie.\n\nDetermined to see the brothers reconciled, Willow despatches Averill with a party invitation to the house of Miss Sickert, where Dalton and his stepson are lodging. Intending on interrogating the dissolute messenger, Miss Sickert is instead dragged into an unwanted existential conversation about her own existence, which raises fears that neither she nor her afternoon guest, the obsequious Bishop Hazelton, are able to allay.\n\nAs the day of the party arrives, Nandy proposes an early morning fishing trip with his father, with the hope that this will bring about a long-sought rapprochement. The planned reconciliation appears to have been thwarted when a storm intercepts the boat, reducing it to a wreck, and depositing its two passengers in the sea, as Willow, Bree, and Kenzie watch with horror from the shore. When the latter calls Miss Sickert with news of the apparent tragedy, she is heartbroken, and begins to make her way to Willow's house through the rain. Both Dalton and Nandy are rescued from the surf, neither knowing that the other is still alive, and thus both are given the opportunity to mourn the loss of the other, and are thereby reconciled when they realise that tragedy has been averted. When both Miss Sickert and Bishop Hazelton arrive somewhat bedraggled at the house, they find the family joined together in celebration, their differences resolved and their collective pasts forgiven. \n\n== Characters ==\n\n* '''Kenzie:''' a retired writer, disgraced by his public affair with a teenager twenty years previously, Kenzie is prone to deep reflection on the shifting patterns of life. Like [[Prospero]] in ''The Tempest'', he suffers a quasi-banishment to Plantation Island, where he perennially feels like a guest in the house of his third wife, Willow, and her forty-year-old son, Averill. Unlike his wife, Kenzie is a firm believer in the numinous. Beset by constant guilt concerning his indiscretion, the ageing writer makes daily entries in a letter, which is by this stage the length of a book, addressed to his tragically deceased lover, Kia. At odds with his past, Kenzie carries a lasting resentment toward his older brother, Dalton, who, as the chair of the charity that Kenzie was volunteering at when he committed the indiscretion, publishes his younger brother's letter of confession in the newsletter.\n\n* '''Dalton:''' the older brother of Kenzie, Dalton lives a highly organised life of solitude. Retired from his career as a professor at a law school, he has ambitions of writing a history of Central Park. Unable to understand why Kenzie has not spoken to him in two decades, Dalton avoids his own past, particularly the remembrance of his two breakdowns: the first of which began while performing the role of best man at Kenzie's first wedding; the second of which occurs after the death of his own wife, when he is overcome by existential questions.\n\n* '''Willow:''' a wealthy resident of Plantation Island, Willow is the third wife of Kenzie Maxwell, having herself been previously married twice. Kenzie's willingness to believe \u201canything\u201d is set against her own belief in \u201cnothing\u201d. Rather than considering matters existential, Willow instead ponders deeply her own past, remembering the death of her second husband, and wondering at Kenzie's inability to bring about reconciliation with his older brother.\n\n* '''Bree:''' born out of Kenzie's indiscretion with a teenage runaway, Kia, Bree's life is characterised by a search for identity. In search of traces of her mother, whose last name is unknown to both her and Kenzie, Bree scours the neighbourhood in [[New York City]] where her mother had previously lived. A graffiti artist, Kia is known to have left her signature sprayed in different forms all over her borough, and Bree has combed the area for any sign of her mother's mark, though without success. \u00a0\n\n* '''Nandy:''' the disaffected and feckless stepson of Dalton, Nandy has endured a series of disappointments in his life, culminating in the tragedy of his mother's untimely death. Dropping out of college to embark upon a summer-long bike tour of the continent, the young man has finally settled down to life as a maintenance worker at a golf course.\n\n* '''Averill:''' abandoning any ambition towards an ordinary life, the forty-year-old Averill has spent his adulthood windsurfing, meditating, and living off the wealth of his mother, Willow, as a permanent resident at her house. He is, as Dale Brown writes, 'the sort of fellow nobody notices',<ref>Brown, W. Dale. (2006). ''The Book of Buechner: a journey through his writings''. Westminster John Knox Press. pp. 361. ISBN <bdi>0-664-23113-6</bdi>. OCLC 255278233.</ref> yet this gives him unusual insight into the lives of fellow inhabitants of the island, whose reverie he disturbs with unwanted existential questions.\n\n* '''Miss Sickert:''' 'another of Buechner's almost villains',<ref>Brown, W. Dale. (2006). ''The Book of Buechner: a journey through his writings''. Westminster John Knox Press. pp. 354. ISBN <bdi>0-664-23113-6</bdi>. OCLC 255278233.</ref> Violet Sickert is the aged matriarch of Plantation Island. Her famed \u201csuppers\u201d are the recognised point of entry into the social life of the island, where she sees her role as supervisory: '\"I try to keep this island afloat like a ship\"', she claims, '\"that's what I do. I try to make the journey as well run and attractive and civilized as possible\"'.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buechner|first=Frederick|title=The Storm|publisher=HarperOne|year=1998|isbn=|location=New York|pages=102}}</ref> Despite her disapproval of Kenzie's past she is beset by her own returning scandal \u2013 the well-worn rumour that her servant, Calvert Sykes, is actually her illegitimate son. \u00a0\n\n== Composition ==\n''The Storm'' was published one year after the release of Buechner's thirteenth novel, ''On the Road with the Archangel'' (1997). Buechner's works published in the late 1990s and early 2000s reveal a preoccupation with Shakespeare's [[Shakespeare's late romances|late romances]]. In an interview given for the ''San Diego Weekly Reader'' in 1997, Buechner revealed his own desire to write novels similar to the late works of Shakespeare:<blockquote>I had my seventieth birthday two summers ago, and I began thinking about things people write when they get to be old codgers. I thought about Shakespeare. I thought about how at the end of his life he wrote these wonderful sort of fairy tale plays like ''The Tempest'' and ''[[The Winter's Tale|The Winter's Tale]]'', and everything ends up wonderfully, and it's sort of too good not to be true.<ref>Judith Moore, 'Reading', ''San Diego Weekly Reader'', December 4 (1997), p.65</ref></blockquote>''The Tempest'', which Dale Brown describes as 'the allusive force'<ref>Brown, W. Dale. (2006). ''The Book of Buechner: a journey through his writings''. Westminster John Knox Press. pp. 342. ISBN <bdi>0-664-23113-6</bdi>. OCLC 255278233.</ref> behind ''The Storm'', is a work that Buechner acknowledges as highly influential throughout his writings. Remembering his school years in his first autobiographical work, ''The Sacred Journey'' (1982), Buechner writes:<blockquote>Mr. Martin had us read wonderful things \u2013 it was he who gave me my love for ''The Tempest,'' for instance \u2013 but it was a course less in literature than in language and the great power that language has to move and in some measure, even to transform the human heart.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buechner|first=Frederick|title=The Sacred Journey|publisher=Harper and Row|year=1982|isbn=|location=New York|pages=69}}</ref></blockquote>In his literary critical work, ''Speak What We Feel'' (2001), published two years after ''The Storm'', the author describes ''The Tempest'' as: <blockquote>[A] fairy tale too good not to be true, where all shadows are finally dispelled and the world seems bathed in a kind of golden haze, as if at the close of his career Shakespeare had reached some kind of golden inner peace within himself.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buechner|first=Frederick|title=Speak What We Feel|publisher=HarperSanFrancisco|year=2001|isbn=|location=New York|pages=149}}</ref></blockquote>Buechner further elucidates this theme in an earlier non-fiction work, ''Telling the Truth: the gospel as tragedy, comedy, and fairy tale'' (1977). Concerning ''The Tempest'', he writes:<blockquote>But at the close of his career, after the period of the great tragedies, Shakespeare turned to something much closer to true fairy tales. He wrote ''Cymbeline,'' where innocence is vindicated and old enemies reconciled, and ''The Winter's Tale,'' where the dead queen turns out not to be dead at all, the lost child, Perdita, restored to those who love her. And he wrote ''The Tempest'' itself, where the same great storm of the world that drowned the Franciscan nuns aboard the ''Deutschland'' and lashed old Lear to madness and stung Job in his despair is stilled by Prospero's magic; and justice is done, and lovers reunited, and the kingdom restored to its rightful king so that in a way it is the beautiful dream of Caliban that turns out to be real and the storm of the world with all its cloud-capped towers and gorgeous palaces and solemn temples that turns out to be the insubstantial pageant that fades into thin air and leaves not a rack behind. Like the last self-portraits of Rembrandt, where the ravaged old face of the painter smiles out of the shadows, it is as if at the end of his career Shakespeare comes out on the far side of the tragic vision of ''Lear'' and ''Macbeth'' and speaks into the night a golden word too absurd perhaps to be anything but true, the laughter of things beyond the tears of things.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buechner|first=Frederick|title=Telling the Truth|publisher=HarperSanFrancisco|year=1977|isbn=|location=New York|pages=87-8}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\n== Themes ==\nBuechner scholar Dale Brown suggests that ''The Storm'', like its predecessor, ''On the Road with the Archangel'', has a 'valedictory'<ref>Brown, W. Dale. (2006). ''The Book of Buechner: a journey through his writings''. Westminster John Knox Press. pp. 366. ISBN <bdi>0-664-23113-6</bdi>. OCLC 255278233.</ref> quality: 'an undertone of goodbye, a kind of joyous sadness that percolates through the very different books, a way of summing up'.<ref>Brown, W. Dale. (2006). ''The Book of Buechner: a journey through his writings''. Westminster John Knox Press. pp. 339. ISBN <bdi>0-664-23113-6</bdi>. OCLC 255278233.</ref> The novel is, in line with the rest of Buechner's work, concerned with existential questions. The return of its central character, Kenzie, to church, and his renewed sense of faith, is balanced against his wife's scepticism, as once more faith and doubt find expression in a domestic setting. In addition to the reoccurrence of such topics as God, death, and forgiveness, there is a further fascination with the process and effect of aging, termed by Brown as an emerging 'grief and exuberance': a Shakespearean 'mix of comedy and tragedy'.<ref>Brown, W. Dale. (2006). ''The Book of Buechner: a journey through his writings''. Westminster John Knox Press. pp. 341-2. ISBN <bdi>0-664-23113-6</bdi>. OCLC 255278233.</ref> \n\n== Critical reception ==\nBuechner's fourteenth novel was warmly received by critics. In his review, written for the ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer|Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', Michael Harrington called ''The Storm'' a 'miniature epic' and a 'quiet marvel', concluding that Buechner 'is one of our greatest novelists'.<ref>Harrington, Michael. \"Miniature Epic of Alienation, Salvation\u201d ''Philadelphia Inquirer,'' February 21 1999, p.4.</ref> Writing in ''[[World and I|The World & I]]'', Maude McDaniel reflected more broadly on Buechner's career as a novelist, suggesting that 'ambiguity has become Buechner's stock in trade [\u2026.] and is probably the key to his success as a religious writer in the studiedly nonreligious culture of the last half of the twentieth century'. Within this line of thinking McDaniel argued that ''The Storm'' represents 'the most ambiguous of all his books'.<ref>Maude McDaniel, \u201cAn Elusive Grace\u201d, ''The World & I'', May 1999, p.278.</ref>\n\nSeveral critics noted the author's use of ''The Tempest'' as a touchstone for the novel. In a review published in the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'', Ruth Coughlin wrote that Buechner, 'a well regarded writer', had published 'a contemporary tale of redemption'. She continues: 'Drawing on both his literary and religious credentials, he has used his latest novel to reinterpret ''The Tempest'''.<ref>Ruth Coughlin, \u201cBooks in Brief: Fiction\u201d, ''New York Times'', January 17, 1999, p.1.</ref> Writing for the ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram|Fort-Worth Star-Telegram]]'', Larry Swindell called ''The Storm'' an 'entirely wonderful [example of a] paraphrase of Shakespeare',<ref>Larry Swindell, '''Tempest'' in a Teapot', ''Fort-Worth Star-Telegram'', December 6, 1998, p.5.</ref> while the ''[[Kirkus Reviews|Kirkus Review]]'' found it to be 'a wonderfully humane and satisfying meditative romance', containing 'a fascinating set of variations on the Shakespearean source, expressed in spare, simple declarative sentences that propel the story forward with commendable swiftness.' The reviewer further noted Buechner's 'skilful' movement between 'the viewpoints of several major characters', before concluding that the novel constitutes 'A marvelous adaptation of Shakespeare\u2014one of the best ever.'<ref>'Review: ''The Storm''', ''Kirkus Review'', November 1<sup>st</sup>, 1998, p.208.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Storm (Buechner novel)}}\n[[Category:20th-century novels]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novels]]\n[[Category:1998-related lists]]\n[[Category:1998 novels]]\n[[Category:American literature]]\n", "name_user": "Bennv3771", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Storm_(Buechner_novel)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nebraska", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Nebraska, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nebraska\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         =\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Nebraska]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]\n| arrival_date    = March 6, 2020\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 1,287<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) {{!}} Health & Human Services|website=dhhs.ne.gov|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://nebraska.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/4213f719a45647bc873ffb58783ffef3|title=COVID-19 Dashboard {{!}} Health & Human Services|website=dhhs.ne.gov|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/us/|title=United States Coronavirus Cases {{!}} Worldometer|website=www.worldometers.info|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 28<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx Nebraska Department of Health & Human Services]\n}}\nThe 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Nebraska]] is part of an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus&nbsp;2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}). As of April 18, 2020, the [[Nebraska Department of Health & Human Services]] (DHHS) has confirmed 1,287 cases and 28 deaths in the state.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Nebraska medical cases chart}}\n\n===March===\n\nOn March 6, Governor [[Pete Ricketts]] announced that the first presumptive positive case of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) had been reported to the Nebraska DHHS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/First-Presumptive-Positive-Case-of-Coronavirus-2019-Reported-to-Nebraska-DHHS.aspx/|title=First Presumptive Positive Case Of Coronavirus 2019 Reported To Nebraska DHHS|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the Nebraska DHHS set up a coronavirus (COVID-19) information line that will allow residents to get answers to general questions and receive information on resources available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Statewide-COVID-19-Information-Line-Opens-for-Residents.aspx/|title=Statewide COVID-19 Information Line Opens For Residents|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, the first and second deaths related to coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) were reported to Nebraska DHHS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Two-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-State.aspx/|title=Two COVID-19 Deaths Reported In State|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Governor Ricketts issued an executive order to expedite the entry of medical professionals into the workforce to prepare for the possibility of a surge in COVID-19 cases and/or the unavailability of some medical professionals due to quarantine restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Issues-Executive-Order-to-Bolster-Healthcare-Workforce.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Issues Executive Order To Bolster Healthcare Workforce|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the third death related to coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) was reported in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Third-COVID-19-Death-Reported-in-State.aspx/|title=Third COVID-19 Death Reported In State|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n\nGovernor Ricketts on April 1 urged Nebraskans to take steps to prevent the spread of COVID-19, but he fell short of issuing a [[stay-at-home order]]. 52 of 93 counties have \"directed health measures\" that include an enforceable ban on gatherings of more than 10 persons and require bars and restaurants to close their dining areas, but Ricketts does not want to extend the restrictions statewide. The state's fourth COVID-19 death was reported on March 31, a [[Buffalo County, Nebraska|Buffalo County]] man in his 90s.<ref>[https://apnews.com/4c60a12dfff86c612b1b126b5fbcbede Ricketts: Nebraskans must \u2018do better\u2019 to slow coronavirus] AP, 1 Apr 2020</ref> The fifth death in the state was reported, a Madison County resident with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Fifth-COVID-19-Death-Reported-in-State.aspx/|title=Fifth COVID-19 Death Reported In State|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe state recorded its sixth death related to COVID-19, a Gage County resident, the county's first case on April 2, 2020. Colfax, Hamilton, Merrick and Otoe Counties also recently reported first cases of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Sixth-COVID-19-Death-Reported-in-State.aspx/|title=Sixth COVID-19 Death Reported In State|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, Mayor [[Jean Stothert]] admonished parkgoers to stop gathering in large groups, specifically mentioning crowding problems last weekend at Standing Bear Lake, Zorinsky Lake, Flanagan Lake, Levi Carter Park, and Walnut Grove Park. Stothert said that the City of Omaha has 260 parks but people must keep a safe 6-foot distance from others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omaha.com/news/local/mayor-stothert-stop-crowding-in-omaha-parks-or-the-city-will-close-them/article_bd2e79b2-7b14-5b28-ad09-2e6a15e539bf.html/|title=Mayor Stothert: Stop crowding in Omaha parks, or the city will close them|website=Omaha World-Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, two deaths were reported in Douglas County related to COVID-19 bringing the state total to eight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Two-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-State-Bringing-Total-to-Eight.aspx/|title=Two COVID-19 Deaths Reported In State Bringing Total To Eight|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Dr. Shane Farritor, an engineering professor at the [[University of Nebraska-Lincoln]] and a team of volunteer builders are set to build face shields ([[personal protective equipment]]) for the health care professionals at risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ketv.com/article/unl-engineers-builders-make-face-shields-for-hospitals-battling-covid-19/32041535/|title=UNL engineers, builders make face shields for hospitals battling COVID-19|website=KETV Omaha|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, four deaths (two residents from Douglas County, one from Custer County and one from Hall County) related to COVID-19 were reported, thus bringing the state total to 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Four-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-State-Bringing-Total-to-12.aspx/|title=Four COVID-19 Deaths Reported In State Bringing Total To 12|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, Lancaster County announced its first COVID-19 related death and Madison County announced its second death adding to the state's total death toll of 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Two-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-Nebraska-Bringing-Total-to-14.aspx/|title=Two COVID-19 Deaths Reported In Nebraska, Bringing Total To 14|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, Governor Ricketts proclaimed April 10\u201330, 2020 as \u201c21 Days to Stay Home and Stay Healthy in Nebraska\" and urged Nebraskans to avoid non-essential errands and limit social gatherings, as infectious disease experts project that the COVID-19 outbreak will be at or near its peak in Nebraska by the end of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Proclaims-21-Days-to-Stay-Home-and-Stay-Healthy.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Proclaims \u201c21 Days To Stay Home And Stay Healthy\u201d & Unveils Six Rules To Keep Nebraska Healthy|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> State's COVID-19 related death toll reached 15 due to the six death in Douglas County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Statewide-Total-for-COVID-19-Deaths-Reaches-15.aspx/|title=Statewide Total For COVID-19 Deaths Reaches 15|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, two new deaths related to COVID-19 were reported in Hall County adding to the state's total of 17 while first cases of COVID-19 were found in Clay and Webster Counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Two-New-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-Nebraska,-Bringing-Statewide-Total-to-17.aspx/|title=Two New COVID-19 Deaths Reported In Nebraska, Bringing Statewide Total To 17|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, first COVID-19 related death reported in Washington County and state's death toll increases to 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/18th-COVID-19-Related-Death-Reported-in-Nebraska.aspx/|title=18th COVID-19 Related Death Reported In Nebraska|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, state's death toll reached 20 due to COVID-19 related deaths in Douglas and Custer counties while Saline County recorded its first case of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/19th-and-20th-COVID-19-Related-Deaths-Reported-in-Nebraska.aspx/|title=19th And 20th COVID-19 Related Deaths Reported In Nebraska|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, Morrill and Howard Counties reported their first cases while fifth death related to COVID-19 was reported in Hall County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/One-New-COVID-19-Related-Death-Reported-in-Nebraska.aspx/|title=One New COVID-19 Related Death Reported In Nebraska|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, two COVID-19 related deaths in Gage County and one in Douglas County increased state's death toll to 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Three-New-COVID-19-Related-Deaths-Reported-in-Nebraska.aspx/|title=Three New COVID-19 Related Deaths Reported In Nebraska|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Governor Ricketts said that the social distancing guidelines will not be lifted all at once and probably some social distancing will continue until there is a vaccine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omaha.com/news/state_and_regional/ricketts-tells-nebraskans-not-to-get-their-hopes-up-about-relaxation-of-social-distancing-rules/article_94e15c73-d6d0-5d93-98f4-15cdb84f2deb.html/|title=Ricketts tells Nebraskans not to get their hopes up about relaxation of social distancing rules|website=Omaha World-Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n\n[[File:2020 Six Rules to Keep Nebraska Healthy.pdf|thumb|Gov. Ricketts' \"Six Rules to Keep Nebraska Healthy\" during the State's response to the ongoing coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic.]]\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"|COVID-19 Cases in Nebraska<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\nUpdated April 18, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:left\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n! scope=\"col\" |Deaths\n! scope=\"col\" |County Population\n(July 2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/data/tables/time-series/demo/popest/2010s-counties-detail.html|title=County Population by Characteristics: 2010-2018|website=United States Census Bureau|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Adams County, Nebraska|Adams]]\n|94\n|1\n|31,511\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Antelope County, Nebraska|Antelope]]\n|1\n|0\n|6,336\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Box Butte County, Nebraska|Box Butte]]\n|1\n|0\n|10,772\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Buffalo County, Nebraska|Buffalo]]\n|49\n|1\n|49,615\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Burt County, Nebraska|Burt]]\n|1\n|0\n|6,488\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Butler County, Nebraska|Butler]]\n|1\n|0\n|8,058\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cass County, Nebraska|Cass]]\n|3\n|0\n|26,159\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cherry County, Nebraska|Cherry]]\n|1\n|0\n|5,761\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cheyenne County, Nebraska|Cheyenne]]\n|4\n|0\n|9,310\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clay County, Nebraska|Clay]]\n|3\n|0\n|6,214\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Colfax County, Nebraska|Colfax]]\n|4\n|0\n|10,881\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cuming County, Nebraska|Cuming]]\n|2\n|0\n|8,940\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Custer County, Nebraska|Custer]]\n|19\n|2\n|10,840\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Dakota County, Nebraska|Dakota]]\n|28\n|0\n|20,083\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Dawson\u00a0County, Nebraska|Dawson]]\n|43\n|0\n|23,709\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Dodge\u00a0County, Nebraska|Dodge]]\n|16\n|0\n|36,791\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Douglas County, Nebraska|Douglas]]\n|273\n|8\n|566,880\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Franklin County, Nebraska|Franklin]]\n|3\n|0\n|3,023\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Furnas County, Nebraska|Furnas]]\n|1\n|0\n|4,715\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Gage County, Nebraska|Gage]]\n|28\n|3\n|21,4