ance]]\n|1\n|0\n|3,532\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Nemaha County, Nebraska|Nemaha]]\n|1\n|0\n|6,958\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Otoe County, Nebraska|Otoe]]\n|1\n|0\n|15,985\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Phelps County, Nebraska|Phelps]]\n|1\n|0\n|8,996\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Pierce County, Nebraska|Pierce]]\n|1\n|0\n|7,142\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Platte County, Nebraska|Platte]]\n|7\n|0\n|33,363\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Polk County, Nebraska|Polk]]\n|5\n|0\n|5,278\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Red Willow County, Nebraska|Red Willow]]\n|1\n|0\n|10,726\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Saline County, Nebraska|Saline]]\n|6\n|0\n|14,350\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sarpy County, Nebraska|Sarpy]]\n|52\n|0\n|184,459\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Saunders County, Nebraska|Saunders]]\n|6\n|0\n|21,303\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Scotts Bluff\u00a0County, Nebraska|Scotts Bluff]]\n|18\n|0\n|35,989\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Seward County, Nebraska|Seward]]\n|2\n|0\n|17,318\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Stanton County, Nebraska|Stanton]]\n|1\n|0\n|5,970\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Washington County, Nebraska|Washington]]\n|20\n|1\n|20,667\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wayne County, Nebraska|Wayne]]\n|1\n|0\n|9,403\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Webster County, Nebraska|Webster]]\n|1\n|0\n|3,533\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[York County, Nebraska|York]]\n|7\n|0\n|13,772\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |TBD\n|39\n|0\n|{{ndash}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |1,287\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |28\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |1,789,657\n|}\n\n===Supplemental information===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"10\" style=\"text-align:center\" |COVID-19 Cases<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\nUpdated April 18, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Total\nCases\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |New\nCases\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Total\nDeaths\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |New\nDeaths\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Active\nCases\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Total Cases/\n1M pop\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Deaths/\n1M pop\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Total\nTests\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Virus\nNot Detected{{asterisk}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Tests/\n1M pop\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:right\" |1,287\n! style=\"text-align:right; background: #ffcc00\" |+149\n! style=\"text-align:right\" |28\n! style=\"text-align:right; background: #ff0000; color: white\" |+4\n! style=\"text-align:right\" |1,237\n! style=\"text-align:right\" |676\n! style=\"text-align:right\" |15\n! style=\"text-align:right\" |14,652\n! style=\"text-align:right\" |13,288\n! style=\"text-align:right\" |7,692\n|}\n\nNOTE: Both state and local health departments are testing and publicly reporting their cases. In the event of a discrepancy between DHHS cases and cases reported by local public health officials, data reported by the local health department should be considered the most up to date.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{asterisk}} Does not include inconclusive results\n\n==University of Nebraska Medical Center==\n\n===Mask reuse experiments===\n\nAmid shortages of personal protective equipment, the [[University of Nebraska Medical Center]] is experimenting with using [[UV light]] to disinfect and reuse masks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kolata |first1=Gina |title=As Coronavirus Looms, Mask Shortage Gives Rise to Promising Approach |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/health/coronavirus-masks-reuse.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===New mobile app===\n\nThe University of Nebraska Medical Center has partnered with [[Apple Inc.]] and students from the [[University of Nebraska at Omaha]] to launch a mobile screening app for COVID-19, 1-Check COVID that will allow people concerned to answer a series of questions and assess their likelihood of having the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omaha.com/livewellnebraska/unmc-and-uno-develop-mobile-screening-app-for-covid-19/article_f5d0baaf-7bfe-5012-9f75-34c79787d21c.html/|title=UNMC and UNO develop mobile screening app for COVID-19|website=Omaha World-Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Social impacts==\n\n===Medicaid===\n\nNebraska Medicaid submitted an 1135 Waiver application to the federal government due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic and Section 1135 allows the federal government to waive certain federal laws to ensure health care services through the emergency. It provides Nebraska Medicaid certain flexibilities and helps Medicaid beneficiaries to receive needed health care services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Nebraska-Medicaid-Submits-1135-Waiver-Application.aspx/|title=Nebraska Medicaid Submits 1135 Waiver Application|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n===Nebraska accommodation project===\n\nThe Nebraska Accommodation Project (NAP) is a joint collaboration between the Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS), the University of Nebraska, and the Nebraska National Guard. Governor Ricketts announced the expansion of NAP program and the provision of space for individuals who are required to quarantine or isolate because of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Pilot-Program-for-COVID-19-Housing-Accommodation-Expands.aspx/|title=Pilot Program For COVID-19 Housing Accommodation Expands|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n\nOmaha World-Herald reported that spring sports in Nebraska high schools are canceled and COVID-19 has topped the effects of world wars, financial depressions and an even deadlier Spanish flu pandemic from 1918-20 when it came to high school sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omaha.com/sports/high-school/pospisil-the-cancellation-of-spring-sports-is-uncharted-territory-for-state-of-nebraska/article_ab11a44b-2a98-5862-ae2f-96e4495c7ea8.html/|title=The cancellation of spring sports is uncharted territory for state of Nebraska|website=Omaha World-Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Directed Health Measures==\n\nGovernor Ricketts issued two Directed Health Measures to restrict gatherings in Cass, Douglas, Sarpy, Lancaster, Dodge, and Saunders counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://governor.nebraska.gov/sites/governor.nebraska.gov/files/doc/press/Governor%20Press%20Release%203-19%20-%20SPANISH.pdf|title=Gov. Ricketts Announces Directed Health Measure for Cass, Douglas, Sarpy, & Washington Counties|date=March 19, 2020|website=governor.nebraska.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://governor.nebraska.gov/press/gov-ricketts-adds-lancaster-saunders-and-dodge-directed-health-measure-cass-douglas-sarpy|title=Gov. Ricketts Adds Lancaster, Saunders, and Dodge to Directed Health Measure for Cass, Douglas, Sarpy, & Washington Counties|website=governor.nebraska.gov}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Governor Ricketts announced the state's third COVID-19 related Directed Health Measure (DHM) that included Butler, Hall, Hamilton, Merrick, Polk, Seward, and York counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Announces-Butler-Hall-Hamilton-Merrick-Polk-Seward-York-Counties-Now-Included-in-States-DHM.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Announces Butler, Hall, Hamilton, Merrick, Polk, Seward, And York Counties Now Included In State's Directed Health Measure|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, Governor Ricketts issued the state's fourth COVID-19 related Directed Health Measure (DHM) that included Burt, Cuming, Madison, and Stanton counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Announces-Burt-Cuming-Madison-&-Stanton-Counties-Now-Included-in-States-DHMs.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Announces Burt, Cuming, Madison, & Stanton Counties Now Included In State's Directed Health Measure|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Governor Ricketts announced the state's fifth COVID-19 related Directed Health Measure (DHM) that included Banner, Box Butte, Cheyenne, Dawes, Deuel, Garden, Grant, Kimball, Morrill, Scotts Bluff, Sheridan, and Sioux counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Announces-Panhandle-Counties-Now-Included-in-States-DHM.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Announces Panhandle Counties Now Included In State's Directed Health Measure|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, Governor Ricketts issued the State's sixth and seventh COVID-19 related Directed Health Measures (DHMs) that included Adams, Buffalo, Clay, Dawson, Franklin, Gosper, Harlan, Kearney, Nuckolls, Phelps, and Webster counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Announces-11-Counties-in-South-Central-Nebraska-Now-Included-in-States-DHMs.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Announces 11 Counties In South-Central Nebraska Now Included In State's Directed Health Measure|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, Governor Ricketts announced the State's eighth COVID-19 related Directed Health Measure (DHM) that included Antelope, Arthur, Boyd, Brown, Cherry, Holt, Hooker, Keya Paha, Knox, Lincoln, Logan, McPherson, Pierce, Rock, and Thomas counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Announces-15-Counties-in-North-and-Central-Nebraska-Now-Included-in-States-DHM.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Announces 15 Counties In North And Central Nebraska Now Included In State's Directed Health Measure|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, State Directed Health Measures (DHMs) were issued to cover all 93 counties in the state until May 11.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Community-Transmission-Identified-in-Gage-County---First-case-reported-in-Cherry-County.aspx/|title=Community Transmission Identified In Gage County - First Case Reported In Cherry County|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, Governor Ricketts announced the State's tenth COVID-19 related Directed Health Measure (DHM) that included new businesses, to bring greater consistency between state and local DHMs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Adds-Additional-Businesses-to-States-DHM.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Adds Additional Businesses To State\u2019s Directed Health Measure|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx/ Information] from the Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services\n* [https://nebraska.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/4213f719a45647bc873ffb58783ffef3 Coronavirus COVID-19 Nebraska Cases Dashboard] from the Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Nebraska]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Health in Nebraska]]\n", "name_user": "Omaha Agilist", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Nebraska"}
{"title_page": "Bush Music Club", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| image         = \n| alt           = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption       = \n| map           = \n| mcaption      = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| formation     = {{start date and age|1954}}\n| extinction    = \n| type          = [[Nonprofit organization]]\n| status        = \n| purpose       = Promotion of Australian folk music and folk dance; publishing of folk music related materials, including \"Singabout\" magazine (1956-1967) and \"Mulga Wire\" (1977-current).\n| headquarters  = [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| coords        = \n| language      = \n| leader_title  = \n| leader_name   = \n| main_organ    = \n| parent_organization = <!-- if one -->\n| affiliations  = <!-- if any -->\n| budget        = \n| name          = Bush Music Club Inc.\n| former name   = \n| image_border  = \n| size          = <!-- default 200px -->\n| msize         = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt          = <!-- map alt text -->\n| map2          = \n| abbreviation  = \n| location      = \n| region_served = [[Australia]]\n| membership    = \n| general       = \n| num_staff     = \n| num_volunteers =\n| website       = http://www.bushmusic.org.au/\n}}\n[[File:BMC-alex-nov14.jpg|thumb|Original Bushwhacker [[Alex Hood]], age 19 when the Club opened in 1954, performs at the Bush Music Club in 2014, in his 79th year.]]\nSydney's '''Bush Music Club''' is the oldest and longest running [[folk music]] performance and education organisation in Australia. Founded in 1954, and still extant as at 2020, it exists to further \"the collection and research of folklore traditions and folk music and to encourage the performance of traditional bush music, song and dance, spoken word, bush poetry and yarns\".<ref name = \"trove_633341\">National Library of Australia: [https://trove.nla.gov.au/people/633341?c=people Bush Music Club (Sydney, N.S.W.)]</ref> It hosts regular events and has published a range of folklore related materials, including the magazine \"Singabout\" from 1956 to 1967, which continues as a section within a subsequent publication \"Mulga Wire\" (1977-current).\n\n==History==\nThe Club was founded in October 1954 by the Australian folklorist and performer [[John Meredith (folklorist)|John Meredith]], together with colleagues from Australia's first \"bush band\" [[The Bushwhackers (band)|The Bushwhackers]], as a social and teaching club with the aim of popularising the style of bush singing and dancing promoted by the band and encouraging others to form their own performing groups; the band would participate by teaching up-and-coming members songs and giving them instruction on playing bush instruments.<ref>McKenry, 2014, p. 136.</ref> An announcement of the proposed formation of the club, in the form of a leaflet available to interested parties, ran as follows:\n<blockquote>THE BUSH MUSIC CLUB\n\nWe have been approached by many singers and instrumentalists who wished to join the \"Bushwhackers\", but we consider that the optimum number for an ensemble such as ours is six. We have been refusing engagements at the rate of three or four a week for several months, not because we want to, but simply for the reasons that we need time to rehearse, we have to work for our living and because we have to get some sleep occasionally.\n\nWe don\u2019t like disappointing people so we have decided to form a club, where in return for a nominal membership fee we will give away our secrets. The \"Bushwhackers\" will help you to learn the accordeon, harmonica, bones, bush bass, lager phone and lots more. We will provide the words and music of our songs and show you how we sing them.\n\nThe inaugural meeting and first rehearsal of the BUSH MUSIC CLUB will take place at the Realist Theatrette, 1st Floor, 188 George Street, on Thursday October 14th, at 7 p.m. sharp.\n\nFurther details may be had from John Meredith, 5 Henry Street, Lewisham, or from any of the \"Bushwhackers\".<ref>Reproduced at [https://blog.bushmusic.org.au/2017/01/minutes-of-bush-music-club-14th-october.html https://blog.bushmusic.org.au/2017/01/minutes-of-bush-music-club-14th-october.html]</ref></blockquote>\n\nInitial office bearers (all members of the original Bushwhackers band) comprised Brian Loughlin as chair,  Alan Scott as secretary/treasurer, Harry Kay as master of ceremonies and Meredith as \"publicity officer\" and future editor of the club's planned publications.<ref name = \"bushmusicblog_2018_10\">Bush Music Club: [https://blog.bushmusic.org.au/2018/10/history-of-bush-music-club-committee.html History of the Bush Music Club - The Committee, the first 25 years.]</ref>\n\n[[File:BMC-alex-nov14-detail.jpg|thumb|List of Life Members of the Bush Music Club as at 2014 (detail of Alex Hood photograph above)]]\nWith Meredith's interest in collecting Australian folksongs, the club's journal \"Singabout\" was started in 1956 as a route to publish and promote a selection of these songs for singing by others, in addition to being an outlet for newly composed songs on Australian themes. (A Club newsletter, also including song transcriptions, etc., had already started in 1955). While Meredith and his colleagues had [[Australian Communist Party]] affiliations, in reality this manifested itself as a general predisposition to sympathy to the concerns of the Australian working class and not to specific furtherance of official Communist Party objectives, although the American folklorist [[John Greenway (folklorist)|John Greenway]], reviewing \"Singabout\" in 1958, lamented that \"folksong collecting and publishing [in Australia] today is in the hands of the Communists\".<ref name = \"Greenway_1958\">Greenway, John (1958): \"Folklore in Australia: Speewa (etc.).\" ''The Journal of American Folklore'', 71: 183-185. doi:10.2307/537710</ref>{{efn|Such a connection was not, of course, without precedent: both the British [[Workers' Music Association]] and the U.S. [[People's Songs]] had similar interests, that is, the overt use of songs as a vehicle for social change, allied strongly with the labour movement.}} Meredith's involvement as an office bearer with the club lasted until at least 1968, where he is listed as assistant editor, having previously been president for 1961 and vice president for 1966.<ref name = \"bushmusicblog_2018_10\" />\n\nLife members included the Australian traditional singers [[Sally Sloane]] and [[Duke Tritton]]; the latter assisted Meredith with his song collecting and also served as club vice president for several terms. Other persons awarded life membership included founder members and original Bushwhackers John Meredith, Jack Barrie, Alan Scott, Brian Loughlin and Harry Kay, resident topical/humorous songwriter [[John Dengate]], and more (refer board illustrated at right).\n\nA selection of performers from the Club, including Meredith and several other of the original Bushwhackers in the early years, performed at festivals and public gatherings as the \"Bush Music Club Concert Party\" and made a number of appearances on record between the mid 1950s and 1960s (see \"Recordings\" section); for David Jones \"Wool Week\" in 1959 they also appeared as \"The Shearer's Band\". These bands, whose membership tended to vary, were comprised of amateur performers who performed for the love of the music, with proceeds of performances going back to support the Club and its other activities. From the 1970s and onwards, many performers who had received their \"apprenticeships\" with the Concert Party went on to form bands of their own, examples being \"The Rouseabouts\", \"Ryebuck\", \"Pinchgut\", \"Selectors\", \"Southern Cross\", \"Sydney Coves\", \"Currawong\" and \"Barangaroo\".<ref name= = \"bmc_concertparty\">Bush Music Club Inc.: [https://www.bushmusic.org.au/bmc_concertparty.shtml Concert Party]</ref>\n\nThe Club rode out the downturn in popular interest in folk music in the 1980s and 1990s. In 2014 the Club celebrated its 60th birthday with a series of concerts, new publications and festival performances,<ref name =\"bushmusic_2014_12\">Bush Music Club: [https://blog.bushmusic.org.au/2014/12/the-ballad-of-heathcote-bushwhackers.html The Ballad of the Heathcote Bushwhackers]</ref> and in 2020 was still offering a regular program of bush dances, dance and music workshops, and Irish traditional music, singing, and poetry sessions at a range of Sydney venues.<ref name=\"BMC_home\">[http://www.bushmusic.org.au/ Bush Music Club Inc.: Home Page]</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n[preliminary listing, probably some missed]\n* 1954 ''Bushwacker Broadsides'':  1) The Old Man. Kangaroo; (2) The Old Bark Hut; (3) Jim Jones at Botany Bay; 4) The Rabbiter's Song; (5) Ho, Give a Fair Go; (6) Hungry Jim the Miner; 7) Wally the Weatherman; (8) The Black Velvet Band; (9) The Bold Kelly Gang; 10) Bound for Darling Harbour; (11) Farewell to Greta (+ more later??)\n* 1955 John Meredith: ''Six authentic Songs from the Kelly Country'' \n* 1956 onwards: \"Singabout\" Magazine (ceased 1967)\n* 1956 John Meredith (editor): ''Songs from Lawson''\n* 1968 John Meredith, Alan Scott & Eric Bolton (editors): ''Singabout songster. Number 1''\n* 1970 Alan Scott: ''A collector's song book: words and music of thirty-one traditional songs collected in Australia''\n* 1970 R. D. Dengate and J. Carlin (editors): ''Songs of the shearer''\n* 1977-current \"Mulga Wire\" Magazine\n* 1979 Bush Music Club: ''Six new dances, composed for the Bush Music Club's Silver Jubilee''\n* 1982 John Dengate: ''My shout!: songs and poems'' (reprinted 2012)\n* 1984 David Johnson: ''Bush dance: a collection of traditional tunes arranged in sets for bush bands''\n* 1985 Bob Bolton (editor): ''Singabout, selected reprints from Singabout, journal of Australian folksong, 1956-1967: an anthology''\n* 1986 Lance Green: ''Bush dance: instructions''\n* 2004 Scott, Gay (editor) ''The Sally Sloane Songbook: Australian traditional singer''\n* 2007 Mike Waters: ''One hundred Dances''\n* 2010 ''Australian Railway Songs''\n* 2012 John Dengate: ''Songs, Poems, Satire and Shouts all the way''\n* 2013 Helen Romeo (compiler): ''Family bush dance: instructions for simple bush dances, suitable for children & family groups''\n\n==Influence==\nSimilar clubs began to appear in the other Australian States, notably the Victorian Bush Music Club (established 1959)<ref name=\"bushmusic_2019_09\">Bush Music Club: [https://blog.bushmusic.org.au/2019/09/60-years-of-victorian-folk-music-club.html 60 years of the Victorian Folk Music Club (est 1959 as the Victorian Bush Music Club) as recorded in Singabout.]</ref>and the Queensland Bush Music Club (also the Queensland Federation of Bush Music groups).\n\n==Recordings==\nThe following list of recordings by the Bush Music Club Concert Party (aka \"The Shearer's Band\") was put together by Bob Bolton in 1983:<ref name = \"bushmusic_2020_02\">The Bush Music Club: [https://blog.bushmusic.org.au/2020/02/getting-record-straight-bush-music-club.html Getting the Record Straight - The Bush Music Club Discography by Bob Bolton, 1983]</ref>\n\n* Bush Music Club (Concert Party) ''Songs from the Shearing Sheds'' FESTIVAL FL-7116; CALENDAR R66-433  Re\u2019issued as BUSH BALLADS, FESTIVAL FL3I-336\n* ''Songs And Poems of Australia'' (With various other artists ) CALENDAR R66-577\n* The Shearer's Band ''Harmony'' Waltzing Matilda, Nine Miles From Gundagai, Botany Bay, Click Go The Shears. Issued by David Jones for \"Wool Week\", 1959.\n* ''Dinki! Di! We (do) love singing Fair Dinkum Aussie Songs'' / (THE BEST): 10th Anniversary Album (FESTIVAL FL31'526 (1964 ) (CALENDAR R66l96) Title depends on which side of the jacket you read!\n* ''Poems in Music, Henry Lawson Poems set to music by the Bush Music Club'' (1966?) FESTIVAL: Mono; FL32\u2014282; Stereo, SFL932-282 CALENDAR R66-587 (St)SR66-9,587\n* ''True Blue Songs of the Outback'' (1974) FESTIVAL L4552314 (Repackaging of Songs From The Shearing Shed & Dinki Di! as double L.P.\n* ''20 Golden Hits'' (1980) FESTIVAL L-25365 (Re-mastering of twenty tracks from earlier B.M.C. L.P.s)\n* ''The Bush Music Club''   7\" 45 rpm FESTIVAL FX 10-163\n* ''16,000 miles from Home''  FESTIVAL FX 10-459\n* ''Nine Miles from Gundagai'' FESTIVAL FX 100-464 (Tracks weren't new work)\n\n==Bibliography==\n* McKenry, Keith, 2014. More Than a Life: John Meredith and the Fight for Australian Tradition. Rosenberg Publishing, 488 pp. ISBN 9781925078145\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bushmusic.org.au/ Official website]\n* Bush Music Club (Sydney, N.S.W.), 2012: The early years (1954-64). A presentation at the National Folk Festival - Canberra, Australia, Saturday 7th April 2012. 1 x DVD; details [https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/190969329 here]\n* [https://blog.bushmusic.org.au/ Bush Music Club blog] - including a large archive section (scanned documents, photographs, etc.) - e.g. 143 posts in 2018, 99 in 2017\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bush Music Club}}\n[[Category:Australian folklore]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations established in 1954]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| image         = \n| alt           = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption       = \n| map           = \n| mcaption      = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| formation     = {{start date and age|1954}}\n| extinction    = \n| type          = [[Nonprofit organization]]\n| status        = \n| purpose       = Promotion of Australian folk music and folk dance; publishing of folk music related materials, including \"Singabout\" magazine (1956-1967) and \"Mulga Wire\" (1977-current).\n| headquarters  = [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| coords        = \n| language      = \n| leader_title  = \n| leader_name   = \n| main_organ    = \n| parent_organization = <!-- if one -->\n| affiliations  = <!-- if any -->\n| budget        = \n| name          = Bush Music Club Inc.\n| former name   = \n| image_bo